# git-guard allowlist — one pattern per line, matched as substring of remote URL
# Lines starting with # are ignored.
#
# A remote URL is approved if it contains any pattern in this file.
# The check applies to: git commit, git push, git tag.
# If a repo has no remote 'origin', all write ops are blocked.
#
# Examples:
#   github.com/your-org      matches all repos in your org (HTTPS remotes)
#   your-company.com         matches any remote on your company's domain
#   github.com/yourname      matches your personal forks (HTTPS remotes)
#
# SSH remotes need a separate pattern — the check is a plain substring match, not
# URL-aware, and SSH uses a colon after the host (git@github.com:you/repo.git) where
# HTTPS uses a slash (https://github.com/you/repo). Add both forms if you use SSH:
#   github.com:yourname      matches your personal forks (SSH remotes)
#
